<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1437,1027,2025]" box="[151,416,1027,1054]" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,416,1027,1054]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,416,1027,1054]" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,299,1027,1054]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">
<taxonomicName authority="Stiles &amp; Remsen, 2019" authorityName="Stiles &amp; Remsen" authorityYear="2019" box="[151,292,1027,1054]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Elliotomyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">Elliotomyia</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[306,416,1027,1053]" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1437,1027,2025]" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,338,1064,1089]" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">Included species</emphasis>
. This genus includes two currently recognized species: 
<taxonomicName authority="Tschudi, 1846" authorityName="Tschudi" authorityYear="1846" box="[933,1335,1064,1089]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Trochilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="chionogaster">
<emphasis box="[933,1178,1065,1089]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">Trochilus chionogaster</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Tschudi, J. J. von" box="[1185,1335,1064,1089]" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" refId="ref1695" refString="Tschudi, J. J. von (1846) Untersuchung uber die Fauna Peruanum. Ornithologie. Schleitlin und Zollikofer, Vienna, 75 pp." type="book" year="1846">Tschudi, 1846</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Berlepsch, 1883" authorityName="Berlepsch" authorityYear="1883" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Leucippus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="viridicauda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">Leucippus viridicauda</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Berlepsch, H. von" box="[358,536,1101,1125]" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" pagination="487 - 494" refId="ref1195" refString="Berlepsch, H. von (1883) Descriptions of six new species of birds from Southern and Central America. The Ibis, 5 (1883), 487 - 494. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1474 - 919 X. 1883. tb 05204. x" type="journal article" year="1883">Berlepsch, 1883</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. Both occur at middle elevations on the eastern slope of the Andes, mainly between 
<quantity box="[151,296,1137,1161]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" unit="m" value="2000.0" valueMax="3000.0" valueMin="1000.0">1000–3000m</quantity>
. Two subspecies are recognized in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tschudi" authorityYear="1846" box="[662,829,1137,1161]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Trochilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="chionogaster">
<emphasis box="[662,829,1137,1161]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">E. chionogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: the nominate in northern and central 
<collectingCountry box="[1228,1277,1137,1160]" name="Peru" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">Peru</collectingCountry>
and 
<emphasis box="[1327,1437,1137,1161]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">hypoleuca</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Gould, J." box="[151,284,1172,1197]" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" pagination="85 - 90" refId="ref1250" refString="Gould, J. (1846) Descriptions of twenty new species of Trochilidae or Humming Birds. Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London, Series 14, 1846, 85 - 90." type="journal article" year="1846">Gould, 1846</bibRefCitation>
from extreme southern 
<collectingCountry box="[540,589,1173,1196]" name="Peru" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">Peru</collectingCountry>
to northern 
<collectingCountry box="[717,827,1173,1197]" name="Argentina" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">Argentina</collectingCountry>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Stiles &amp; Remsen, 2019" authorityName="Stiles &amp; Remsen" authorityYear="2019" box="[837,1090,1173,1197]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Elliotomyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="viridicauda">
<emphasis box="[837,1090,1173,1197]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">Elliotomyia viridicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is limited to central 
<collectingCountry box="[1309,1361,1173,1196]" name="Peru" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">Peru</collectingCountry>
, where it is locally sympatric with 
<emphasis box="[453,503,1209,1232]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">E. c.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="(Schuchmann 1999)" authorityName="Schuchmann" authorityYear="1999" baseAuthorityName="Schuchmann" baseAuthorityYear="1999" box="[512,881,1209,1233]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Trochilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="chionogaster">
<emphasis box="[512,651,1209,1233]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">chionogaster</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Schuchmann, K. - L." box="[667,873,1209,1233]" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" pagination="468 - 680" refId="ref1431" refString="Schuchmann, K. - L. (1999) Family Trochilidae (hummingbirds). In: del Hoyo, J., Elliot, A. &amp; Sargatal, J. (Eds.), Handbook of the Birds of the World. Vol. 5 n Barn-owls to Hummingbirds. Lynx Edicions, Barcelona, pp. 468 - 680." type="book chapter" year="1999">Schuchmann 1999</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Where they occur together (in the Marañón River watershed), 
<taxonomicName authority="Stiles &amp; Remsen, 2019" authorityName="Stiles &amp; Remsen" authorityYear="2019" box="[282,405,1245,1269]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Elliotomyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="viridicauda">
<emphasis box="[282,405,1245,1269]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">viridicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is found mainly in the canopy and borders of humid forest, whereas 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schuchmann" baseAuthorityYear="1999" box="[1152,1291,1245,1269]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Trochilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="chionogaster">
<emphasis box="[1152,1291,1245,1269]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">chionogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
prefers drier, more open, shrubby vegetation (
<bibRefCitation author="Schulenberg, T. S. &amp; Stotz, D. F. &amp; Lane, D. F. &amp; O'Neill, J. P. &amp; Parker, T. A. III." box="[491,747,1281,1305]" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" refId="ref1496" refString="Schulenberg, T. S., Stotz, D. F., Lane, D. F., O'Neill, J. P. &amp; Parker, T. A. III. (2009) Birds of Peru. Princeton University Press, Princeton, New Jersey, 656 pp." type="book" year="2009">
Schulenberg 
<emphasis box="[632,685,1281,1305]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">et al.</emphasis>
2009
</bibRefCitation>
), as does the allopatric 
<emphasis box="[992,1102,1281,1305]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">hypoleuca</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Robbins, M. B. &amp; Schulenberg, T. S. &amp; Lane, D. F. &amp; Cuervo, A. M. &amp; Binford, L. C. &amp; Nyari, A. S. &amp; Combe, M. &amp; Arbelaez-Cortes, E. &amp; Wehtje, W. &amp; Lira-Noriega, A." box="[1114,1327,1281,1305]" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" pagination="31 - 51" refId="ref1328" refString="Robbins, M. B., Schulenberg, T. S., Lane, D. F., Cuervo, A. M., Binford, L. C., Nyari, A. S., Combe, M., Arbelaez-Cortes, E., Wehtje, W. &amp; Lira-Noriega, A. (2013) Abra Maracunca, dpto. Puno, Peru, revisited: vegetation cover and avifauna change over a 30 - year period. Bulletin of the British Ornithologists' Club, 133 (1), 31 - 51." type="journal article" year="2013">
Robbins 
<emphasis box="[1210,1263,1281,1305]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">et al.</emphasis>
2013
</bibRefCitation>
). All three taxa have uniform bronzy-green upperparts, white underparts speckled or shaded with bronzy-green laterally, and black bills but with the basal half of the mandible reddish; they are similar in size (ca. 
<quantity box="[994,1090,1352,1376]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="5.5" metricValueMax="6.2" metricValueMin="4.8" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" unit="g" value="5.5" valueMax="6.2" valueMin="4.8">4.8–6.2g</quantity>
, bills averaging 
<quantity box="[1262,1373,1353,1377]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.15" metricValueMax="2.3" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" unit="mm" value="21.5" valueMax="23.0" valueMin="20.0">20–23mm</quantity>
, wing chords averaging 
<quantity box="[341,452,1388,1412]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.7" metricValueMax="5.9" metricValueMin="5.5" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" unit="mm" value="57.0" valueMax="59.0" valueMin="55.0">55–59mm</quantity>
, tails 
<quantity box="[515,628,1389,1413]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.95" metricValueMax="3.1" metricValueMin="2.8" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" unit="mm" value="29.5" valueMax="31.0" valueMin="28.0">28–31mm</quantity>
); males tend to have shorter bills but longer wings and tails. The taxa differ most notably in tail color and pattern. The tail of 
<taxonomicName authority="Stiles &amp; Remsen, 2019" authorityName="Stiles &amp; Remsen" authorityYear="2019" box="[676,799,1425,1449]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Elliotomyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="viridicauda">
<emphasis box="[676,799,1425,1449]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">viridicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is mostly green above and dull, dark grayish-bronze below, but the inner webs of most rectrices of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schuchmann" baseAuthorityYear="1999" box="[578,717,1461,1485]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Trochilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="chionogaster">
<emphasis box="[578,717,1461,1485]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">chionogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are broadly whitish to pale gray basally; the tail of 
<emphasis box="[1283,1393,1461,1485]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">hypoleuca</emphasis>
has more extensive white on the outer rectrices, which are rather boldly white-tipped in the females. 
<bibRefCitation author="Robbins, M. B. &amp; Schulenberg, T. S. &amp; Lane, D. F. &amp; Cuervo, A. M. &amp; Binford, L. C. &amp; Nyari, A. S. &amp; Combe, M. &amp; Arbelaez-Cortes, E. &amp; Wehtje, W. &amp; Lira-Noriega, A." box="[1205,1437,1497,1521]" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" pagination="31 - 51" refId="ref1328" refString="Robbins, M. B., Schulenberg, T. S., Lane, D. F., Cuervo, A. M., Binford, L. C., Nyari, A. S., Combe, M., Arbelaez-Cortes, E., Wehtje, W. &amp; Lira-Noriega, A. (2013) Abra Maracunca, dpto. Puno, Peru, revisited: vegetation cover and avifauna change over a 30 - year period. Bulletin of the British Ornithologists' Club, 133 (1), 31 - 51." type="journal article" year="2013">
Robbins 
<emphasis box="[1302,1357,1497,1521]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">et al.</emphasis>
(2013)
</bibRefCitation>
suggested that 
<emphasis box="[308,418,1533,1557]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">hypoleuca</emphasis>
may merit species rank largely based upon its vocalizations, but until genetic data and a detailed analysis of sonograms become available, we retain it as a subspecies here. We designate 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schuchmann" baseAuthorityYear="1999" box="[1093,1232,1569,1593]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Trochilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="chionogaster">
<emphasis box="[1093,1232,1569,1593]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">chionogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as the 
<typeStatus box="[1307,1353,1569,1593]" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">type</typeStatus>
species of 
<emphasis box="[180,312,1605,1629]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">
<taxonomicName authority="Stiles &amp; Remsen, 2019" authorityName="Stiles &amp; Remsen" authorityYear="2019" box="[180,308,1605,1629]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Elliotomyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">Elliotomyia</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="195" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1437,1027,2025]" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1641,1665]" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">Etymology.</emphasis>
The genus name honors Daniel Giraud Elliot for his important early contributions to clarifying the generic taxonomy of the hummingbirds. To this eponym, we add the suffix “myia” (Greek for “fly”), which has been used several times elsewhere to denote the small size of the hummingbirds.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="196" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1437,1027,2025]" lastBlockId="1.[151,1437,154,826]" lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="196" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,316,1748,1772]" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Stiles &amp; Remsen, 2019" authorityName="Stiles &amp; Remsen" authorityYear="2019" box="[324,448,1749,1773]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Elliotomyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[324,448,1749,1773]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">Elliotomyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be diagnosed genetically from various other genera formerly presumed to be closely related (
<bibRefCitation author="Stiles, F. G. &amp; Remsen, J. V. Jr. &amp; McGuire, J. A." box="[238,436,1785,1809]" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" pagination="401 - 424" refId="ref1551" refString="Stiles, F. G., Remsen, J. V. Jr. &amp; McGuire, J. A. (2017 a) The generic classification of the Trochilini (Aves: Trochilidae): Reconciling taxonomy with phylogeny. Zootaxa, 4353 (3), 401 - 424. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4353.3.1" type="journal article" year="2017">
Stiles 
<emphasis box="[306,360,1785,1809]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">et al.</emphasis>
2017a
</bibRefCitation>
). Differences in plumage and morphology of 
<taxonomicName authority="Stiles &amp; Remsen, 2019" authorityName="Stiles &amp; Remsen" authorityYear="2019" box="[925,1049,1785,1809]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Elliotomyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[925,1049,1785,1809]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">Elliotomyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from these are relatively subtle, but taken together with biogeography also permit diagnosis. Both 
<taxonomicName authority="Stiles &amp; Remsen, 2019" authorityName="Stiles &amp; Remsen" authorityYear="2019" box="[810,934,1821,1845]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Elliotomyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[810,934,1821,1845]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">Elliotomyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species were included in 
<taxonomicName box="[1206,1316,1821,1844]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Leucippus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1206,1316,1821,1844]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">Leucippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the past, but were transferred to 
<taxonomicName box="[409,504,1857,1881]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Amazilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[409,504,1857,1881]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">Amazilia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
due to plumage similarities (
<bibRefCitation author="Zimmer, J. T." box="[825,979,1856,1881]" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" pagination="1 - 31" refId="ref1722" refString="Zimmer, J. T. (1950) Studies of Peruvian birds, no. 59: the genera Polytmus, Leucippus and Amazilia. American Museum Novitates, 1475, 1 - 31." type="journal article" year="1950">Zimmer 1950</bibRefCitation>
; see 
<bibRefCitation author="Stiles, F. G. &amp; Remsen, J. V. Jr. &amp; McGuire, J. A." box="[1034,1235,1857,1881]" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" pagination="401 - 424" refId="ref1551" refString="Stiles, F. G., Remsen, J. V. Jr. &amp; McGuire, J. A. (2017 a) The generic classification of the Trochilini (Aves: Trochilidae): Reconciling taxonomy with phylogeny. Zootaxa, 4353 (3), 401 - 424. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4353.3.1" type="journal article" year="2017">
Stiles 
<emphasis box="[1102,1158,1857,1881]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">et al.</emphasis>
2017a
</bibRefCitation>
, b). However, this “green-and-white” style of plumage is subject to widespread homoplasy; moreover, the similar species formerly placed in 
<taxonomicName authority=", Agyrtria" authorityName="Agyrtria" box="[151,348,1929,1953]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Amazilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,348,1929,1953]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">Amazilia, Agyrtria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chubb" authorityYear="1916" box="[381,485,1929,1952]" class="Aves" family="Aves (awaiting allocation)" genus="Agyrtrina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Aves (awaiting allocation)" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[381,485,1929,1952]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">Agyrtrina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are mostly lowland species of northern and eastern South America. All share the bicolored bill with 
<emphasis box="[246,377,1965,1989]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">
<taxonomicName authority="Stiles &amp; Remsen, 2019" authorityName="Stiles &amp; Remsen" authorityYear="2019" box="[246,373,1965,1989]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Elliotomyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">Elliotomyia</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
but most have brighter white underparts and more emerald-green upperparts; some such as 
<taxonomicName authority="(Bourcier &amp; Mulsant)" authorityName="Bourcier &amp; Mulsant" baseAuthorityName="Bourcier &amp; Mulsant" baseAuthorityYear="1846" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Amazilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="franciae">
<emphasis box="[1347,1436,1965,1989]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">franciae</emphasis>
(Bourcier &amp; Mulsant)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Lesson)" authorityName="Lesson" baseAuthorityName="Lesson" baseAuthorityYear="1829" box="[436,658,2001,2025]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Amazilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brevirostris">
<emphasis box="[436,558,2001,2025]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">brevirostris</emphasis>
(Lesson)
</taxonomicName>
also are strongly bronze on the rump and tail; Middle American 
<taxonomicName authority="(Bourcier &amp; Mulsant)" authorityName="Bourcier &amp; Mulsant" baseAuthorityName="Bourcier &amp; Mulsant" baseAuthorityYear="1846" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Amazilia" kingdom="Animalia" lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="196" order="Apodiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="195" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="candida">
<emphasis box="[1350,1436,2001,2025]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="195">candida</emphasis>
(Bourcier &amp; Mulsant)
</taxonomicName>
is considerably smaller and entirely bronze-green above and on the tail, with an indistinct dusky terminal band. The only Andean species, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bourcier &amp; Mulsant" baseAuthorityYear="1846" box="[595,684,190,214]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Amazilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="196" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="franciae">
<emphasis box="[595,684,190,214]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="196">franciae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, has clean white underparts and bright blue (males) or blue-green (females) crown and nape. Genetic data support placement of all of these species in different genera, including 
<taxonomicName authority=", Chlorestes" authorityName="Chlorestes" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Chrysuronia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="196" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="196">Chrysuronia, Chlorestes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName authority="(Stiles et al. 2017 a)" authorityName="Stiles" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Stiles" baseAuthorityYear="2017" box="[300,646,262,286]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Uranomitra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="196" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[300,427,262,285]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="196">Uranomitra</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Stiles, F. G. &amp; Remsen, J. V. Jr. &amp; McGuire, J. A." box="[441,638,262,286]" pageId="1" pageNumber="196" pagination="401 - 424" refId="ref1551" refString="Stiles, F. G., Remsen, J. V. Jr. &amp; McGuire, J. A. (2017 a) The generic classification of the Trochilini (Aves: Trochilidae): Reconciling taxonomy with phylogeny. Zootaxa, 4353 (3), 401 - 424. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4353.3.1" type="journal article" year="2017">
Stiles 
<emphasis box="[509,556,262,286]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="196">et al</emphasis>
. 2017a
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,154,826]" pageId="1" pageNumber="196">
The species formerly placed in 
<taxonomicName box="[541,651,298,321]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Leucippus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="196" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[541,651,298,321]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="196">Leucippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are now allocated to several genera based on genetic data, and all differ from 
<taxonomicName authority="Stiles &amp; Remsen, 2019" authorityName="Stiles &amp; Remsen" authorityYear="2019" box="[210,334,334,358]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Elliotomyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="195" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[210,334,334,358]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="196">Elliotomyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species in their all-black bills. The genus 
<taxonomicName box="[786,896,334,357]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Leucippus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="196" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[786,896,334,357]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="196">Leucippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as currently circumscribed (
<emphasis box="[1202,1229,334,358]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="196">cf.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Stiles, F. G. &amp; Remsen, J. V. Jr. &amp; McGuire, J. A." box="[1235,1429,334,358]" pageId="1" pageNumber="196" pagination="401 - 424" refId="ref1551" refString="Stiles, F. G., Remsen, J. V. Jr. &amp; McGuire, J. A. (2017 a) The generic classification of the Trochilini (Aves: Trochilidae): Reconciling taxonomy with phylogeny. Zootaxa, 4353 (3), 401 - 424. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4353.3.1" type="journal article" year="2017">
Stiles 
<emphasis box="[1301,1349,334,358]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="196">et al</emphasis>
. 2017a
</bibRefCitation>
) includes only 
<taxonomicName authority="(Bourcier)" authorityName="Bourcier" baseAuthorityName="Bourcier" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[299,507,370,394]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Leucippus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="196" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fallax">
<emphasis box="[299,388,370,394]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="196">L. fallax</emphasis>
(Bourcier)
</taxonomicName>
, restricted to the arid northern coastal lowlands of 
<collectingCountry box="[1041,1146,370,394]" name="Colombia" pageId="1" pageNumber="196">Colombia</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1196,1309,370,394]" name="Venezuela" pageId="1" pageNumber="196">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
; its uniform buffy underparts and outer rectrices broadly tipped with dull white are distinctive. Compared with 
<emphasis box="[1217,1348,406,430]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="196">
<taxonomicName authority="Stiles &amp; Remsen, 2019" authorityName="Stiles &amp; Remsen" authorityYear="2019" box="[1217,1344,406,430]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Elliotomyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="195" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">Elliotomyia</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
the two species of 
<emphasis box="[266,395,442,466]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="196">Thaumasius</emphasis>
are duller, more brownish-olive above; 
<taxonomicName authority="Sclater" authorityName="Sclater" box="[830,1049,442,466]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Leucippus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="196" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="taczanowskii">
<emphasis box="[830,968,442,466]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="196">taczanowskii</emphasis>
Sclater
</taxonomicName>
has mostly grayish-drab underparts and a paler throat specked with dusky or green, whereas 
<taxonomicName authority="(Simon)" authorityName="Simon" baseAuthorityName="Simon" box="[777,929,478,502]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Leucippus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="196" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="baeri">
<emphasis box="[777,833,478,502]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="196">baeri</emphasis>
(Simon)
</taxonomicName>
has uniform, dull buffy-brown underparts and outer rectrices broadly tipped with dull white. Both occur in arid matorral vegetation at lower elevations, 
<taxonomicName box="[1271,1409,514,538]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Leucippus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="196" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="taczanowskii">
<emphasis box="[1271,1409,514,538]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="196">taczanowskii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the upper Urubamba valley and 
<taxonomicName box="[495,551,550,574]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Leucippus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="196" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="baeri">
<emphasis box="[495,551,550,574]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="196">baeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the Pacific Tumbesian region. 
<taxonomicName authority="(Gould)" authorityName="Gould" baseAuthorityName="Gould" baseAuthorityYear="1862" box="[913,1268,550,574]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Taphrospilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="196" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hypostictus">
<emphasis box="[913,1177,550,574]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="196">Taphrospilus hypostictus</emphasis>
(Gould)
</taxonomicName>
is considerably larger than the species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Stiles &amp; Remsen, 2019" authorityName="Stiles &amp; Remsen" authorityYear="2019" box="[423,547,586,610]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Elliotomyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="195" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[423,547,586,610]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="196">Elliotomyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with whitish underparts strongly spotted with green except on the lower abdomen; it inhabits the interior of humid forest on the eastern Andean slopes from 
<collectingCountry box="[939,1018,622,646]" name="Bolivia" pageId="1" pageNumber="196">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
to southern 
<collectingCountry box="[1151,1259,622,646]" name="Colombia" pageId="1" pageNumber="196">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, mostly at lower foothill elevations. 
<taxonomicName authority="(Gould)" authorityName="Gould" baseAuthorityName="Gould" box="[359,716,658,682]" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Talaphorus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Apodiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="196" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="chlorocercus">
<emphasis box="[359,625,658,682]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="196">Talaphorus chlorocercus</emphasis>
(Gould)
</taxonomicName>
is darker, duller green above and grayish below, sparsely speckled with brighter green on the throat and sides; its lateral rectrices have largely gray bases, a dusky subterminal band and gray tips; it occurs in the upper Amazonian lowlands on the banks and islands of larger rivers (
<bibRefCitation author="Schulenberg, T. S. &amp; Stotz, D. F. &amp; Lane, D. F. &amp; O'Neill, J. P. &amp; Parker, T. A. III." box="[1131,1395,730,754]" pageId="1" pageNumber="196" refId="ref1496" refString="Schulenberg, T. S., Stotz, D. F., Lane, D. F., O'Neill, J. P. &amp; Parker, T. A. III. (2009) Birds of Peru. Princeton University Press, Princeton, New Jersey, 656 pp." type="book" year="2009">
Schulenberg 
<emphasis box="[1274,1329,730,754]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="196">et al.</emphasis>
2009
</bibRefCitation>
). In sum, the genetic and plumage differences correlate with ecological and distributional features distinguishing all of these genera.
</paragraph>
